\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum gate with fast kick
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Ultrafast operation with Adiabatic Rapid Passage(ARP) pulse
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two kinds of control phase gates proposed in the trapped ion system
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "garcia2003speed,garcia2005coherent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: the 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\sigma_{z}}}$
\end_inset

 gate and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 gate.
 They both create spin-dependent force so different entanglement gate could
 accumulate desired phase in the phase space.
 Entanglement between internal state could be realized through the common
 motional quantum bus (phonon modes) coupling to each states in the ion
 trap.
 At the end of the gate, the motional state and internal state will decouple
 meanwhile the desired phase are accumulated.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{z}$
\end_inset

 gate will create driven spin-dependent AC-stark shifts between the qubit
 energy levels and not create qubit flipping
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "leibfried2003experimental,duan2004scaling,PhysRevLett.97.050505,zhu2006arbitrary,steane2014pulsed,schafer2018fast"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which shaped continuous pulses are optimized for desired optical force.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The originally scheme of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 gate was proposed by Garcia-Ripoll, Zoller and Cirac (GZC)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "garcia2003speed,garcia2005coherent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 gate require ultrafast speed single qubit operation: with the speed higher
 than the period of the trap with large momentum transferring, and even
 with displacement exceeding Lamb-Dicke limit (
\begin_inset Formula $kx_{0}\ll1$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "garcia2003speed"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where k is the wave vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the expansion of the ground motional state wave packet.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 will create qubit flipping accompanying with the large spin-dependent momentum
 kicks (force)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haljan2005spin,miao2007strong"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this proposal, arbitrary fast ultrafast and high fidelity entanglement
 gate could be reached by adding more pulse, which satisfies the relationship
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{Gate}\propto N_{pulse}^{-2/3}$
\end_inset

.
 One need to optimize the number and arrival time of the kicks sequences
 to satisfy the the desired phase accumulated and decoupling between qubit
 state and motional state.
 Theoretical works have given a lot hints on the sequences design, for example
 GZC scheme
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "garcia2003speed,garcia2005coherent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Fast Robust Antisymmetric Gate
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bentley2013fast,bentley2015trapped"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Duan's proposal for finite laser repetition rate
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "duan2004scaling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Recent experiment researches show progresses in this area
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mizrahi2014quantum,wong2017demonstration,johnson2017ultrafast"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with mode-locked laser and create the two qubits entanglement gate with
 large phase space displacement.
 Disadvantage of their methods (75% fidelity in 19 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

s hard to achieve high repetition rate; hard to change the direction of
 the kicks; large numbers of kicks (more than 200 kicks) for a single gate;
 not flexible to design the sequence to match the repetition rate of the
 pulse laser).
 One main problem of this scheme is that the finite laser repetition limits
 the gate fidelity and makes the optimization hard to operate.
 High repetition rate laser: 300 MHz
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hussain2016ultrafast"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 5GHz
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "heinrich2018ultrafast"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and novel optimization scheme
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gale2019optimised"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have been proposed to solve the problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we propose to use Adiabatic Rapid Passage (ARP) pulse for the spin-dependen
t kick sequence, which also used in atom interferometry, which separate
 paths of different energy level and accumulate the difference phase between
 different paths.
 There have been large areas and momentum transfers proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "muller2008atom,kotru2015large"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The ARP is also used in the ion trap on states shuttling and motional states
 cooling
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wunderlich2007robust"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We find that with increasing the power of pulses (which is also the requirement
 of addressing single ion) and optimizing the parameters, high speed and
 fidelity single qubit flipping and ultrafast two qubit entanglement gate
 in hundreds nanosecond level could be achieved.
 More importantly, with the high sampling rate Arbitrary Function Generator
 (AWG), the wave packet, phase and the sequences time of the pulse could
 be controlled precisely and modulated continuously, which get rid of the
 problem of the repetition rate.
 Along with so many novel pulse sequences design, sub-microsecond level
 entanglement gate could be reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Method}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We make a model of eight energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{171Yb^{+}}}$
\end_inset

 ions which shows in Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:EightEnergyLevel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The qubits are encoded onto the ground hyperfine states of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{171Yb^{+}}}$
\end_inset

 ions: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2S_{1/2}\left|F=0,m_{F}=0\right\rangle }}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\textrm{\mathbf{\textrm{\textrm{2S_{1/2}\left|F=1,m_{F}=0\right\rangle }}}}}$
\end_inset

 with an energy splitting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{HF}=2\pi\times12.6428$
\end_inset

 GHz.
 The Raman beams are detuning by hundreds of GHz from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

 manifold and they are far less than the 100 THz splitting between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{3/2}}}$
\end_inset

.
 So we do not need to consider the coupling to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{3/2}}}$
\end_inset

 manifold and only view 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

 as the virtual energy level.
 The hyperfine splitting in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

 manifold is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}=2\pi\times2105$
\end_inset

 MHz.
 We then consider linear effect (
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\times1.4$
\end_inset

 MHz/G for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2S_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\times0.47$
\end_inset

 MHz/G for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}}$
\end_inset

) and quadratic effect (
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\times310.8$
\end_inset

 Hz/
\begin_inset Formula $G^{2}$
\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{171Yb^{+}}}$
\end_inset

 zeeman splitting under DC magnetic field which defines the quantized axis.
 Then we can define
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
2S_{1/2}\left|F=0,m_{F}=0\right\rangle  & \equiv\left|0\right\rangle \nonumber \\
2S_{1/2}\left|F=1,m_{F}=0\right\rangle  & \equiv\left|1\right\rangle \nonumber \\
2P_{1/2}\left|F=1,m_{F}=-1\right\rangle  & \equiv\left|2\right\rangle \nonumber \\
2P_{1/2}\left|F=1,m_{F}=1\right\rangle  & \equiv\left|3\right\rangle 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/apple/Documents/GitHub/Fastgate/kick/fig/fidelity_1.pdf
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:EightEnergyLevel"

\end_inset

(a) scheme of GZC proposal in our realization.
 The pulse sequences are separated into integer groups, with in each group
 momentum transferring in the same direction.
 Here the ultrafast flipping is realized with the fast AWG modulated CW
 laser, which benefits for high controllability of the sequence time and
 phase without the limit of repetition rate.
 The sequence time of each pulse is shift by the operation time of each
 kicks from the ideal optimized condition, for considering actual gate time.
 (b) spin-dependent momentum kick.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 satisfies Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{x,y}=\Delta\mp\delta_{HF}$
\end_inset

.
 Bi-chromatic lights propagate in opposite direction and shine perpendicularly
 to the ion chain.
 When the first 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 pulse flips the qubit state, laser intensity and frequency need to be switched
 to keep kicking in the same direction with fixed polarization.
 (c) Energy level and ARP pulse diagram.
 Qubit states are encoded onto the hyperfine energy levels of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{171Yb^{+}}}$
\end_inset

 ion (
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

).
 The ions will absorb a photon to the virtual energy level and emit another
 photon which gives the spin-dependent momentum transfer of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\hbar k$
\end_inset

.
 The bi-chromatic lights have a large single-photons detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and two-photons detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

.
 Static magnetic field separate the zeeman energy levels and lights with
 polarization 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x},\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 couple between zeeman energy levels.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

-polarized light cannot drive dipole transition between qubit states (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2S_{1/2}}},m_{F}=0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\textrm{2P_{1/2}}},m_{F}=0$
\end_inset

 energy level for corresponding dipole matrixes equal to zero (selection
 rule).
 Then consider linear polarized light, which could be decomposed into 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 polarized light:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sigma_{x} & =\frac{1}{2}(\sigma^{+}+\sigma^{-})\\
\sigma_{y} & =\frac{1}{2}(\sigma^{+}-\sigma^{-}),\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{+}$
\end_inset

 polarized light can couple between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|2\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-}$
\end_inset

 polarized light can couple between 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|3\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, we apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{y}$
\end_inset

 polarization light to drive the Raman Process.
 The intensity of the bi-chromatic lights are set to satisfy the condition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{I_{x}}{I_{y}}=\frac{\Delta-\delta_{HF}}{\Delta+\delta_{HF}}\label{eq:3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for AC-stark shifts are proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{I}{\Delta}$
\end_inset

, we could then obtain the relationship: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{I_{x}}{\Delta}+\frac{I_{y}}{\Delta+\delta_{HF}}=\frac{I_{y}}{\Delta}+\frac{I_{x}}{\Delta-\delta_{HF}}$
\end_inset

 to cancel the first order AC-stark shift on the qubit level caused by two
 lights.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 here is the single-phonon detuning.
 The concept of ARP methods are widely used in nuclear resonance and atomic
 physics for robust two energy level system transition.
 For the Raman ARP (the scheme is shown in Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:EightEnergyLevel"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), the whole system can be viewed as an effective two-level system: the
 Rabi frequency is the two-phonon 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{eff}$
\end_inset

 here; the detuning across the resonance is the two-phonon detuning sweeping
 during the inversion of population, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(t)=\delta_{HF}-(w_{y}-w_{x})$
\end_inset

.
 Similar to the teo level condition, the Bloch vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\vec{s}}}$
\end_inset

 will precesses around the effective rotation axis 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Omega(t)|=\sqrt{\Omega_{eff}^{2}(t)+\delta^{2}(t)}$
\end_inset

, and satisfy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\vec{s}}{dt}=\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{s},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
if the Bloch vector can adiabatically follow 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Omega}(t)$
\end_inset

 on the Bloch spheres from one pole to another.
 We generate the fast ARP pulse with the intensity envelope 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)$
\end_inset

 and two-phonon detuning with the form following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I_{x,y}(t) & =I_{x,y}\sin(\pi t/\tau)\nonumber \\
\delta(t) & =\delta_{0}\cos^{2}(\pi t/\tau),\label{eq:5}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 is the whole operation time for a single flipping and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 are the intensity of the bi-chromatic laser.
 Advantage compare to the Stimulate Raman Process (STIRAP)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kotru2015large"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Simulation Result}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We simulate the result of ultrafast bit flipping in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0.2$
\end_inset

 ns with high fidelity (which corresponds to 5 GHz repetition rate).
 We first show the simulation result for fast qubit flipping.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:parameter"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we search for optimized parameters ARP pulse with different single photon
 detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, two photon detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and laser intensity s (in the unit of the saturation intensity for 
\begin_inset Formula $2P_{1/2}$
\end_inset

 manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{sat}=510.3$
\end_inset

 W/
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}$
\end_inset

 ).
 The operation time for single flipping duration 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is set to be 0.2 ns.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:fidelity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we study the high fidelity kick operation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 optimized to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\times121.5$
\end_inset

 GHz and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\times7.05$
\end_inset

 GHz, the laser intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{y}$
\end_inset

 is set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times10^{7}\times I_{sat}$
